( As a result, four USAF commanders were relieved of their commands, numerous other USAF personnel were disciplined and/or decertified to perform certain types of sensitive duties, and further cruise missile transport missions from – and nuclear weapons operations at – Minot Air Force Base were suspended,1)
( Based on this and other incidents, on 5 June 2008, Secretary of the Air Force Michael Wynne and Chief of Staff of the Air Force General T Michael Moseley were asked for their resignations, which were given,1)
( During this period, the warheads were not protected by the various mandatory security precautions for nuclear weapons,1)
( In October 2008, in response to recommendations by a review committee, the USAF announced the creation of Air Force Global Strike Command to control all USAF nuclear bombers, missiles, and personnel,1)
( In addition, the USAF issued new nuclear weapons handling instructions and procedures,1)
( Six AGM-129 ACM cruise missiles, each loaded with a W80-1 variable yield nuclear warhead, were mistakenly loaded onto a United States Air Force (USAF) B-52H heavy bomber at Minot Air Force Base in North Dakota and transported to Barksdale Air Force Base in Louisiana,1)
( The investigation concluded that nuclear weapons handling standards and procedures had not been followed by numerous USAF personnel involved in the incident,1)
